        <h1 class="max-w-3xl font-display font-bold text-3xl sm:text-4xl text-slate-100 leading-tight tracking-tight mb-6">
          Read-Only MCP Removes a Failure Class, But Only if the Whole Tool Boundary Is Actually Read-Only
        </h1>
        <p class="max-w-3xl text-lg text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
          Read-only MCP matters because it can remove an entire mutation failure class. But the claim only holds when the surrounding runtime preserves a real inspect-only boundary instead of leaving write-capable side doors open.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 pt-10 pb-24">
      <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-4 mb-10">
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-emerald-500/20 bg-emerald-500/5 p-4">
          <div class="text-[11px] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-emerald-400 mb-2">Inspect</div>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">Read and observe without mutation. The cleanest trust class to hand an agent early.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-amber/20 bg-amber/5 p-4">
          <div class="text-[11px] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-amber mb-2">Write</div>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">Changes data or configuration. Should stay visibly separate from inspect-only surfaces.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-rose-500/20 bg-rose-500/5 p-4">
          <div class="text-[11px] font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-rose-400 mb-2">Execute</div>
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">Triggers side effects that may be indirect, broad, or hard to reverse.</p>
